@rapunzelnorway She lost the HRH quite some time ago actually, I believe around the time Ingrid was born. In Norway now, they have a Royal House and Royal Family. Only the monarch, the monarch's heir, and the heir's heir and their spouses are considered part of the Royal House, so currently that is King Harald, Queen Sonja, Crown Prince Haakon, Crown Princess Mette-Marit, and their eldest daughter, Princess Ingrid Alexandra. The king's surviving sister, Princess Astrid; his daughter, Princess Martha Louise, and his grandson Prince Sverre Magnus are all considered part of the Royal Family only, not the Royal House. I am not sure about whether or not the children of Princess Astrid, the late Princess Raghnild, and Princess Martha are considered part of the Royal Family too--in the Netherlands, the Royal House is the King, Queen, their three daughters, his mother Princess Beatrix who was the former queen, his brother Constantijn and his wife, and his aunt Margriet who married a Dutch professor, who is also part of the royal house despite not holding a title himself. But the Dutch royal family includes also all the descendants of Queen Juliana--so that includes the rest of Beatrix's grandchildren, plus the children and grandchildren of all her sisters as well, which is quite a lot of people, the majority of whom don't even have a title.

But in Norway, their royal family is much smaller and also newer, so different rules.

Only those in direct line to the crown are styled as HKH (Hans/Hennes Kongelige Høyhet) which is the Norwegian version of His/Her Royal Highness, which is Haakon, MM and Ingrid only. When necessary, Astrid, Martha, and Magnus are able to use His/Her Highness in order to ensure they are given proper precedence at international royal events, but within Norway, they don't have those styles at all.
